From Equation (7), one can realize that the Q-dependence of the strength of a Förster field is governed by two competing factors: (1) the linear Q term and (2) the exponential decay e−Qd. The linear Q-dependent factor (1) originates from the fact that the strength of the dipole-dipole interaction between a point-dipole (QD) and dipoles periodically distributed over a 2D plane (TMD-ML) increases with increasing the periodicity of the in-plane distributed dipoles, i.e., increasing Q. As increasing Q, the planar density of dipoles increases, and the total FRET rate is enhanced. On the other hand, the exponential decay factor is associated with the near-field nature of the Förster field, which contains the evanescent mode decaying exponentially along the z direction (∝ e−κd), characterized by an imaginary wave vector, kz = iκ. Since the magnitude of the wave vector of a radiation, k=kx2+ky2+kz2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$k=\sqrt{{k}_{x}^{2}+{k}_{y}^{2}+{k}_{z}^{2}}$$\end{document}, should remain invariant to fulfill the momentum conservation law, the imaginary wave vector carried by the evanescent mode allows the momentum of the in-plane components of a Förster field exceeds the light-cone edge, i.e., kx2+ky2>qc\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sqrt{{k}_{x}^{2}+{k}_{y}^{2}} \,>\, {q}_{{{{\rm{c}}}}}$$\end{document}, and enables the Förster field to couple MFDX’s. As a result of the two competing factors, the magnitude of the matrix element of Förster coupling, M̃S,Q\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
